            "body": "2026-07-13 Ziyang research note mapped to Stage 3 Layer utility evaluation:\n\n1. Known-state camera-to-robot branch: DREAM detects robot keypoints and uses forward kinematics + PnP; CtRNet's released ROS path consumes image + joint state; CtRNet-X adds partial-visibility robustness and an optional RGB-D refinement path. These are camera-extrinsics baselines, not observation-only robot-state estimators.\n2. Unknown-state Robot Layer branch: RoboPose estimates joint angles and 6D camera-to-robot pose from a single RGB image, while HoRoPose targets real-time RGB pose estimation without known robot state. Both still require explicit robot model/camera assumptions in the benchmark manifest.\n3. Differentiable rendering branch: keep Dr. Robot as a render-and-compare probe, but record the current blocker that Franka is not plug-and-play before treating it as an executable baseline.\n4. Rigid Object Layer branch: normalize the meeting-note typo to official Any6D. Its released path is RGB-D/calibration dependent and uses a single RGB-D anchor plus masks/camera intrinsics, so it is a calibrated rigid-object oracle rather than the default generated-video route.\n5. Deformable branch: optical flow is still untested. Run one cloth/cable smoke first, report 2D tracks independently, and only lift to 3D when depth/intrinsics are available with uncertainty recorded.\n\nNext gate: use one clip manifest to compare calibrated oracle vs estimated depth/intrinsics vs layer-only inputs. For each method log URDF, joint state, K, depth, mask, visibility, runtime, VRAM, pose/track error, and failure cases. Do not claim Layer utility from a route that receives stronger sensor or calibration inputs than its baseline.",
